# ESP32-MQTT-Sensor-Node

> NOTE: THIS IS AN EXPANSION OF ESP32-Realtime-Sensor-Monitor

ESP32 project that reads temperature and humidity using a BME280 sensor and publishes live data to an MQTT broker. 
Any device in the world can subscribe to the data topics and receive live sensor readings. 
No delay used anywhere, everything runs on millis.

---

## ✨ Features

- 🌡️ Measures temperature and humidity using a BME280 sensor
- 📡 Publishes live data to MQTT broker (`broker.hivemq.com`)
- 🌐 Accessible from anywhere in the world via MQTT
- 📊 Publishes statistics — min/max temperature and threshold count
- 🖥️ Displays live data on an SSD1306 OLED screen (128x64)
- ⚡ Live data streaming via WebSockets — no page refresh
- 🧠 Non-blocking timing with `millis()` → stays responsive
- 🖱️ Interactive button:
  - **Short press**: shows "Button pressed!" on the OLED
  - **Long press (≥ 2 sec)**: cycles through three modes:
    - 📊 Sensor Mode — live temperature and humidity
    - ℹ️ Info Mode — device IP address and uptime
    - 📈 Stats Mode — min/max temperature and threshold count
  - **Auto-return (after 5 sec)**: returns to Sensor Mode automatically
- 🌡️ Smart alert system: reacts to high temperature with LED, OLED, and web feedback

---

## 📡 MQTT Topics

| Topic | Description |
|-------|-------------|
| `esp32/sensor/temperature` | Live temperature in °C |
| `esp32/sensor/humidity` | Live humidity in % |
| `esp32/sensor/minTemp` | Lowest recorded temperature |
| `esp32/sensor/maxTemp` | Highest recorded temperature |
| `esp32/sensor/threshold` | Number of times threshold exceeded |

---

## 🧰 Components Required

- ESP32 Development Board (e.g., ESP32 DevKit)
- BME280 temperature/humidity sensor (I²C)
- SSD1306 OLED display (128x64, I²C)
- Breadboard and jumper wires
- Micro-USB cable
- RED LED
- 2x 220 Ohm Resistor
- 1x pushbutton

---

## 🔌 Wiring (I²C Bus)

| ESP32 Pin | Function | Connected To |
|----------|----------|--------------|
| 3.3V | Power | VCC of BME280 + OLED |
| GND | Ground | GND of BME280 + OLED + Button (one side) |
| GPIO21 | SDA | SDA of BME280 + OLED |
| GPIO22 | SCL | SCL of BME280 + OLED |
| GPIO4 | Input | Button (other side) |
| GPIO2 | Output | LED + 220Ω resistor |

Note: The button is connected between GPIO 4 and GND. The code enables the internal pull-up resistor, so no external resistor is required.

> 💡 Ensure both devices use **different I²C addresses** (BME280: `0x76`, OLED: `0x3C`).

---

## ▶️ Usage

1. Install required libraries via PlatformIO — add these to `platformio.ini`:

```ini
lib_deps =
    adafruit/Adafruit BME280 Library@^2.2.3
    adafruit/Adafruit SSD1306@^2.5.7
    adafruit/Adafruit GFX Library@^1.11.6
    mathieucarbou/ESPAsyncWebServer@^3.3.23
    mathieucarbou/AsyncTCP@^3.3.2
    knolleary/PubSubClient
```

2. Create `secrets.h` and fill in your WiFi credentials:

```cpp
#define AP_SSID     "your-network-name"
#define AP_PASSWORD "your-password"
```

3. Upload the code to your ESP32
4. Open `https://www.hivemq.com/demos/websocket-client/` in your browser
5. Connect to `broker.hivemq.com`
6. Subscribe to `esp32/sensor/temperature` and other topics
7. Watch live data arrive from your ESP32

